WEBVTT

00:06.484 --> 00:06.702
.

00:06.745 --> 00:09.357
- Previously on "Shooter."

00:10.923 --> 00:12.490
- Your former boss was holding
on to something of mine--

00:12.534 --> 00:16.059
A decryption device.
We call it the God Box.

00:16.103 --> 00:18.235
- We don't have it.
- Then Gregson does.

00:18.279 --> 00:19.758
- Show me the card.

00:19.802 --> 00:21.412
[suspenseful music]

00:21.456 --> 00:23.414
- Still doing their dirty work,
I see.

00:23.458 --> 00:26.548
♪

00:26.591 --> 00:28.158
- She slipped it to me.

00:28.202 --> 00:30.073
- That card is all Alice wants
right now.

00:30.117 --> 00:32.554
Whatever it is, they're gonna
turn over the world to get it.

00:32.597 --> 00:34.338
- Why did you pay Rick Culp
to help Jimmy Poole escape

00:34.382 --> 00:35.339
from prison?
- No idea what you're

00:35.383 --> 00:37.167
talking about.

00:37.211 --> 00:38.603
- Now, if you and your daddy
don't give me the cash,

00:38.647 --> 00:40.649
I'm gonna tell Swagger
everything I know and then--

00:40.692 --> 00:43.086
[groaning]

00:43.130 --> 00:45.132
- I served with a kid
not much older than you.

00:45.175 --> 00:47.351
A Corporal named Gutierrez,
shot himself in the leg

00:47.395 --> 00:48.874
horsing around one night.

00:48.918 --> 00:50.789
- I'm looking for some
information on a Marine

00:50.833 --> 00:52.878
wounded in Vietnam in 1970.

00:52.922 --> 00:54.619
Uh, Corporal Gutierrez.

00:54.663 --> 00:55.838
Who's this?

00:55.881 --> 00:57.709
- Ramon Gutierrez.

00:57.753 --> 01:00.147
Patricia Gregson said you
wanted to talk to me.

01:08.720 --> 01:10.331
- For all this trouble,
this guy better know something

01:10.374 --> 01:11.897
about Atlas.

01:11.941 --> 01:13.638
- Gregson made sure
to put us in touch with him

01:13.682 --> 01:16.206
before she died.
Had to be a reason.

01:16.250 --> 01:18.469
- It's risky.
- Gutierrez won't meet with us

01:18.513 --> 01:20.776
unless we follow
his instructions.

01:26.434 --> 01:29.698
All right, you go right,
I'll go left.

01:29.741 --> 01:32.179
We'll meet up at bus 168
to Bloomsville.

01:32.222 --> 01:34.137
- And if there's trouble?
- Handle it, and we'll meet

01:34.181 --> 01:36.835
back at the bunker in D.C.
- Copy that.

01:36.879 --> 01:43.451
♪

01:51.807 --> 01:54.157
- Yeah, there it is.
Silver Spring. Come on.

01:54.201 --> 01:56.420
[dark music]

01:56.464 --> 02:03.514
♪

02:12.306 --> 02:14.612
[indistinct P.A. announcement]

02:14.656 --> 02:18.181
[dark, tense music]

02:18.225 --> 02:25.232
♪

02:48.255 --> 02:50.300
- [sighs]

02:50.344 --> 02:51.823
Where the hell are you?

02:51.867 --> 02:58.656
♪

02:58.700 --> 03:00.615
- Yo, yo!
Hold up, hold up!

03:00.658 --> 03:04.532
♪

03:04.575 --> 03:06.838
I got on the wrong bus.
Sorry, man.

03:06.882 --> 03:13.889
♪

03:17.632 --> 03:19.721
- Cutting it close, no?

03:19.764 --> 03:20.983
- I wanted to make sure
we were clean.

03:21.026 --> 03:22.637
- Ladies and gentlemen,

03:22.680 --> 03:24.247
I apologize for the delay...
- Now what?

03:24.291 --> 03:25.683
- All Gutierrez said was

03:25.727 --> 03:28.469
get off at the stop
in Bloomsville, Maryland.

03:28.512 --> 03:30.688
So we just sit tight.

03:30.732 --> 03:36.912
♪

03:39.697 --> 03:42.787
- I don't think--I can't--
I don't think I can do this.

03:44.920 --> 03:47.792
- This decryption card says
"Titan Incorporated."

03:47.836 --> 03:50.708
Your friend, Rebecca Simmons,
works for Titan Incorporated.

03:50.752 --> 03:53.885
- I know, but I've barely
spoken to her since college.

03:53.929 --> 03:55.409
We just like each other's posts

03:55.452 --> 03:57.019
and wish each other
happy birthday.

03:57.062 --> 03:58.542
She's just gonna be suspicious
that I wanna see her

03:58.586 --> 03:59.978
all of a sudden.

04:00.022 --> 04:01.589
- Not if you pretend
it's a dinner date.

04:01.632 --> 04:03.678
Flirt and ask her if she's
seeing anyone,

04:03.721 --> 04:04.940
then guide the conversation
to work

04:04.983 --> 04:06.724
then the decryption card.

04:06.768 --> 04:08.291
- I don't like toying
with people's emotions.

04:08.335 --> 04:09.379
- You're not doing it
to be cruel.

04:09.423 --> 04:10.989
You're doing it to survive.

04:11.033 --> 04:12.904
Because if you can't put your
contacts to good use

04:12.948 --> 04:13.949
and make this happen,
then you're not

04:13.992 --> 04:15.429
worth our protection.

04:16.430 --> 04:17.909
- Who are you, again?

04:17.953 --> 04:19.650
- A friend.
- Um, okay.

04:19.694 --> 04:21.522
Well, no offence, friend,
but that's not the kind

04:21.565 --> 04:22.523
of protection I want, okay?

04:22.566 --> 04:23.741
Is she one of us now?

04:23.785 --> 04:26.004
- Harris, you said you wanted
to help.

04:26.048 --> 04:28.268
So help.
- [sighs]

04:28.920 --> 04:29.965
Well, I guess it's
too late now.

04:30.008 --> 04:31.053
There she is.

04:33.447 --> 04:35.710
- Okay, make sure you sit
by a window,

04:35.753 --> 04:37.320
otherwise we can't protect you.
- Okay.

04:37.364 --> 04:38.800
- And keep your phone on.
We'll be listening.

04:38.843 --> 04:40.584
- Okay.
- And don't mention the card

04:40.628 --> 04:42.717
right away.
Be smooth.

04:43.848 --> 04:44.980
- Smooth.
[clears throat]

04:47.635 --> 04:50.333
- Even if Rebecca has intel,
Harris doesn't have the skills

04:50.377 --> 04:51.465
to extract it.

04:52.988 --> 04:54.032
- I know.

04:55.860 --> 04:57.732
- So what are we doing here?

04:59.342 --> 05:00.822
- We need to keep an eye
on them.

05:01.649 --> 05:03.346
- You know, I get why you
wouldn't tell him

05:03.390 --> 05:05.087
the whole plan,
but why keep me in the dark?

05:06.871 --> 05:08.525
- Because I don't trust you.

05:20.537 --> 05:22.060
- You notice?

05:22.104 --> 05:24.541
This bus just got on
a highway headed south

05:24.585 --> 05:27.022
when Bloomsville is north.

05:27.065 --> 05:28.676
- I'll go ask the bus driver
if he got lost.

05:28.719 --> 05:30.591
- No, I'll go.

05:30.634 --> 05:33.420
I don't want you shooting the
guy for making a wrong turn.

05:37.946 --> 05:40.949
[dramatic music]

05:40.992 --> 05:48.043
♪

05:51.525 --> 05:53.004
- Isaac.
- Don't.

05:53.048 --> 05:59.707
♪

05:59.750 --> 06:00.751
- Gutierrez?

06:00.795 --> 06:03.145
- Nice to meet you.

06:04.407 --> 06:07.410
[dramatic music]

06:07.454 --> 06:14.504
♪

06:16.463 --> 06:16.680
.

06:16.724 --> 06:19.553
[suspenseful music]

06:20.118 --> 06:21.424
♪

06:21.468 --> 06:23.383
- Where the hell
did you get this?

06:23.426 --> 06:25.950
- Your online dating profile.

06:25.994 --> 06:27.561
Said I was looking
for a man in uniform.

06:27.604 --> 06:29.171
- [laughs]

06:29.214 --> 06:32.000
You don't think that's me
in the photo.

06:32.043 --> 06:34.524
But...you can't
change the past.

06:34.568 --> 06:37.135
You can't hide from it,
either.

06:40.530 --> 06:44.273
Accidental discharge after
a drunken celebration

06:44.316 --> 06:46.406
one night post-mission.

06:46.449 --> 06:48.277
Your father tell you
that story?

06:48.320 --> 06:50.540
- All that would be in a file
somewhere for Atlas to have.

06:50.584 --> 06:52.324
- [chuckles]
That's true.

06:52.368 --> 06:54.414
Which is why I've been hiding
since Earl Swagger

06:54.457 --> 06:56.111
was assassinated.

06:56.154 --> 06:57.460
- Well, if you're that scared,
you must know

06:57.504 --> 06:59.288
why they killed him.

06:59.331 --> 07:02.117
- I wouldn't endanger my
associates by letting them

07:02.160 --> 07:04.119
hear my secrets.

07:04.162 --> 07:05.163
Follow me.

07:05.207 --> 07:12.257
♪

07:14.303 --> 07:16.566
- So you're not Atlas,
but you're a drug trafficker?

07:16.610 --> 07:19.134
- I needed an income when
I went off the grid.

07:19.177 --> 07:20.440
And this is medicine,

07:20.483 --> 07:22.137
not heroin.
- So, what's the plan?

07:22.180 --> 07:23.312
You gonna lecture us
on the healing powers of weed,

07:23.355 --> 07:25.053
or can we get down
to business?

07:25.096 --> 07:26.228
- We're not doing anything
until I know you're not

07:26.271 --> 07:27.316
being tracked.

07:28.535 --> 07:30.145
Change your clothes.

07:30.188 --> 07:32.234
[click]

07:32.277 --> 07:34.584
- These don't look my size.

07:34.628 --> 07:37.239
- You could have a device
sewn into the fabric.

07:37.282 --> 07:39.415
- Come on, man, we got nothing
to be ashamed of.

07:39.459 --> 07:41.504
- I'm being modest
for your sake.

07:43.114 --> 07:46.596
- I wanted to reach out when I
heard Senator Hayes died,

07:46.640 --> 07:50.295
but I just figured you
probably needed space.

07:50.339 --> 07:54.169
- Yeah, yeah, that was--
that was difficult.

07:54.212 --> 07:57.520
Uh...
- I'm glad you called.

07:57.564 --> 07:59.304
[laughs]
It just always felt like

07:59.348 --> 08:00.523
you were one of the good guys.

08:00.567 --> 08:03.657
- Oh, well, you know, I try.

08:03.700 --> 08:05.528
You know how D.C. is.
- Yeah, oh, my God, right?

08:05.572 --> 08:08.662
- Down is up and up is down.
Right, yeah, it's bad.

08:08.705 --> 08:15.712
♪

08:17.758 --> 08:20.369
I--I found something when I
was going through, uh,

08:20.412 --> 08:23.459
Hayes' stuff,
cleaning it out.

08:23.503 --> 08:26.070
Um, this little card thing.

08:27.332 --> 08:28.725
- Real smooth, Harris.

08:30.205 --> 08:32.207
- Do you know what that is?
- Yeah, and there's no way

08:32.250 --> 08:33.469
you should have this. This is
way above your clearance.

08:33.513 --> 08:35.079
- Okay, well, what are
you doing with it?

08:35.123 --> 08:37.081
- I am taking this key to HQ
and reporting you.

08:37.125 --> 08:38.692
Otherwise I'm getting fired,
maybe even facing prosecution.

08:38.735 --> 08:40.258
- Okay, hold on, hold on,
hold on.

08:40.302 --> 08:41.433
I came to you in good faith,
okay?

08:41.477 --> 08:43.392
Just--what is it?
What is it?

08:43.435 --> 08:45.350
- Why didn't you turn this in
with the rest of Hayes' things?

08:45.394 --> 08:47.135
- Because the Senator
told me to keep it

08:47.178 --> 08:49.572
in case, you know,
something happened to him.

08:49.616 --> 08:51.095
- But he didn't tell you
what it does?

08:51.139 --> 08:53.620
You're a shitty liar, Harris.

08:53.663 --> 08:54.882
[ominous chords]

08:54.925 --> 08:57.449
[grunting]

08:57.493 --> 09:01.541
♪

09:01.584 --> 09:02.716
- You come with me.
Now.

09:02.759 --> 09:06.110
[overlapping voices,
commotion]

09:06.154 --> 09:07.372
We're on our way.

09:07.416 --> 09:10.506
[tense music]

09:10.550 --> 09:16.207
♪

09:19.428 --> 09:20.560
Come on, let's go.

09:20.603 --> 09:27.610
♪

09:32.223 --> 09:35.618
- All right, there you go.

09:35.662 --> 09:37.141
Thanks.

09:49.240 --> 09:50.633
- What do you got there?

09:50.677 --> 09:54.463
- Oh, Bob Lee is being asked
to give, uh,

09:54.506 --> 09:58.293
an official statement
in a missing persons case.

09:58.336 --> 09:59.860
- Wait, who is missing?

09:59.903 --> 10:02.210
- Mmm, Rick Culp.

10:02.253 --> 10:06.649
Says that he was a guard at the
Wilson Prison and Bob Lee was

10:06.693 --> 10:09.173
one of the last people to speak
to him before he disappeared.

10:10.479 --> 10:11.654
Mmm.

10:12.786 --> 10:15.658
- Well, this--this law firm
is no joke.

10:15.702 --> 10:17.225
Has he ever gotten one
of these before?

10:18.835 --> 10:21.751
- No, but, I mean,
people come after Bob Lee

10:21.795 --> 10:23.666
in so many different ways.

10:23.710 --> 10:27.714
Always seems harmless at first,
but I've learned to see

10:27.757 --> 10:29.367
through the smoke screen.

10:30.194 --> 10:31.413
- So, what do you do?

10:31.456 --> 10:32.806
You just ignore it?

10:34.764 --> 10:36.810
- I would if it came from some
two-bit lawyer,

10:36.853 --> 10:40.640
but it is the biggest law firm
in Texas, so...

10:42.293 --> 10:43.643
There's money behind it.

10:43.686 --> 10:46.646
[dramatic music]

10:46.689 --> 10:50.475
♪

10:50.519 --> 10:52.695
- Okay, we jumped through
all your hoops.

10:52.739 --> 10:54.218
Now talk.

10:54.262 --> 10:55.785
Why did Atlas kill my father?

10:55.829 --> 10:58.353
- Your father was gonna tell
the world about them.

10:58.396 --> 11:01.878
Not just that they existed,
but how they operated.

11:02.749 --> 11:05.012
Where they got their money.
Everything.

11:05.055 --> 11:06.709
- What do you mean
by everything?

11:06.753 --> 11:08.450
- We already know that his dad
was one of Atlas'

11:08.493 --> 11:10.844
founding members.
- He was indeed.

11:10.887 --> 11:13.368
He was also living proof
of some of Atlas'

11:13.411 --> 11:15.587
earliest war crimes.

11:15.631 --> 11:19.679
Your father had innocent blood
on his hands.

11:24.422 --> 11:24.596
.

11:24.640 --> 11:26.816
- All right, you're trying
to say he was a war criminal?

11:27.556 --> 11:28.426
Come on, man, he ran

11:29.645 --> 11:29.689
one black ops unit.
There were probably

11:30.602 --> 11:30.733
dozens of others just like it.

11:31.647 --> 11:31.995
- But those units didn't go on

11:33.040 --> 11:34.476
to become Atlas.
Your father's did.

11:34.519 --> 11:35.869
- Yeah, but he didn't
know that.

11:35.912 --> 11:38.001
If he had, he--
- He would have done what?

11:38.045 --> 11:40.308
Stopped it?
[laughs]

11:40.351 --> 11:42.397
Pull your head out
of your ass.

11:42.832 --> 11:45.661
Deep down you know he had
a darkness inside him.

11:46.923 --> 11:49.056
- War puts a darkness inside
of everyone.

11:49.099 --> 11:52.407
- There's war,
and there's what we did...

11:52.973 --> 11:55.627
which was a whole new
level of evil.

11:55.671 --> 11:58.500
Your father wasn't just
following orders.

11:58.543 --> 12:00.502
He was vetting targets,

12:00.545 --> 12:03.679
volunteering his tactical
expertise.

12:03.723 --> 12:07.465
And no one had to twist his arm
to do it.

12:08.815 --> 12:10.512
- You gotta give us
some names and dates.

12:10.555 --> 12:11.905
Intel we can verify.

12:14.734 --> 12:17.345
- July, 1970.

12:17.388 --> 12:19.086
By then, our orders
weren't coming down

12:19.129 --> 12:21.001
through the chain
of command.

12:21.044 --> 12:22.785
- Where were your orders
coming from?

12:22.829 --> 12:26.093
- A shadow faction
inside the Pentagon.

12:26.136 --> 12:28.704
Not the kind you find
on any org chart.

12:28.748 --> 12:30.532
- Sergeant Swagger.

12:30.575 --> 12:32.316
♪

12:32.360 --> 12:33.622
- Hi.

12:33.665 --> 12:34.841
- You should know
that I consider

12:34.884 --> 12:36.799
this meeting unnecessary.

12:36.843 --> 12:38.932
I'm only here because
the secretary insisted.

12:38.975 --> 12:42.631
- He must place a high
value on this target, then.

12:42.674 --> 12:44.328
- Katherine Mayfield.

12:44.372 --> 12:48.419
Top of her class at MIT.
Kissinger recruited her.

12:48.463 --> 12:51.118
She was the brain
behind our operations.

12:51.161 --> 12:53.947
- Tell me I didn't just
travel 8,200 miles

12:53.990 --> 12:56.558
for you to show me
stick figure drawings.

12:56.601 --> 12:58.603
- The missions you're sending
us lack an understanding

12:58.647 --> 13:00.388
of what's really going on here
on the ground.

13:00.431 --> 13:02.085
- They've been successful
by my count.

13:02.129 --> 13:03.957
- Because I've been able
to improvise around

13:04.000 --> 13:05.654
your lack of imagination.

13:05.697 --> 13:07.961
Your math is good
at picking missions,

13:08.004 --> 13:09.484
but it's horrible
at predicting

13:09.527 --> 13:12.400
how things will go down
in combat.

13:12.443 --> 13:16.012
For instance, our next mission,
Dat Van Thieu.

13:16.056 --> 13:17.840
You got us backed up against
this river,

13:17.884 --> 13:20.060
and you've bet our asses on him
being in his bedroom

13:20.103 --> 13:21.670
when we arrive.

13:21.713 --> 13:24.368
- He will be.
I've studied his routines.

13:24.412 --> 13:25.935
It's almost a certainty.

13:25.979 --> 13:28.459
- The only certainty is that
things will go sideways

13:28.503 --> 13:30.374
once bullets start flying.

13:30.418 --> 13:31.854
♪

13:31.898 --> 13:33.987
- What do you suggest?

13:34.030 --> 13:37.991
- Katherine Mayfield spent
the next 40 years

13:38.034 --> 13:41.081
planning Atlas missions.

13:41.124 --> 13:43.997
Thanks to your dad, she
learned how to trap targets

13:44.040 --> 13:45.825
no matter which way
they tried to run.

13:48.566 --> 13:50.830
- Nadine and I learned
that Atlas uses

13:50.873 --> 13:54.790
probability calculations to
position their assassins.

13:54.834 --> 13:57.662
- How do you know my dad met
with this Mayfield person

13:57.706 --> 13:59.621
at all if you weren't there?

13:59.664 --> 14:02.929
- Earl told us in the mission
brief that night.

14:02.972 --> 14:06.541
And then we went out
to do the job

14:06.584 --> 14:09.544
using our new operating
principles.

14:09.587 --> 14:12.155
Everything changed.
No uniforms.

14:12.199 --> 14:16.072
No dog tags.
Non-American weapons.

14:16.116 --> 14:18.422
♪

14:18.466 --> 14:21.425
Our target was a VC general
who slipped across the border

14:21.469 --> 14:23.906
to secure black market weapons
for the Vietcong.

14:23.950 --> 14:27.431
[jungle animal sounds]

14:27.475 --> 14:30.565
[tense music]

14:30.608 --> 14:32.610
[man grunting]

14:34.786 --> 14:36.876
[muffled grunting]

14:43.621 --> 14:47.712
Earl and I were responsible
for killing the general.

14:47.756 --> 14:49.453
One glance around
the target's room,

14:49.497 --> 14:50.977
and I knew something was off.

14:51.020 --> 14:53.196
Yeah, there were
guards outside,

14:53.240 --> 14:55.938
but he didn't have any
military gear or weapons.

14:55.982 --> 14:59.072
Just some fancy-ass suits
and shoes.

14:59.115 --> 15:02.945
- What are you waiting for?
- This guy is no general.

15:02.989 --> 15:04.947
- This guy is the mission.

15:04.991 --> 15:07.819
♪

15:07.863 --> 15:08.864
[gunfire]

15:08.908 --> 15:09.996
[thud]

15:10.039 --> 15:11.954
Check it out.
I'll cover.

15:11.998 --> 15:15.610
♪

15:15.653 --> 15:18.656
- Oh, my God.
- What?

15:18.700 --> 15:23.139
♪

15:23.183 --> 15:25.968
- We need to report this.
- What good would it do?

15:26.012 --> 15:28.101
What's done is done.

15:28.144 --> 15:29.624
Let's go.

15:29.667 --> 15:35.151
♪

15:35.195 --> 15:36.979
- This crazy old man
has wasted our time.

15:37.023 --> 15:40.243
- What reason would I have
to make any of this up?

15:40.287 --> 15:42.985
- Hey, you gotta listen to this
like he's not talking about

15:43.029 --> 15:45.945
your father.
- Yeah, but he is.

15:45.988 --> 15:47.990
And I know who my father was.

15:48.034 --> 15:49.644
He was a guy who seemed
to enjoy Vietnam way more

15:49.687 --> 15:51.167
than he liked
raising his family.

15:51.211 --> 15:53.213
And his way of dealing with
that was running off

15:53.256 --> 15:54.692
and being a hero all the time.

15:54.736 --> 15:56.216
But he had a code.

15:56.259 --> 15:57.913
There were lines
he wouldn't cross.

15:57.957 --> 15:59.132
Yeah, he was a hard ass,

15:59.175 --> 16:00.698
but deep down he was
a good man.

16:00.742 --> 16:02.918
- You've got no clue
what it's like.

16:02.962 --> 16:05.529
Your father's entire focus was
to complete the mission

16:05.573 --> 16:06.661
no matter the cost.

16:06.704 --> 16:09.229
Over and over and over again.

16:09.272 --> 16:11.187
That type of grind...

16:11.231 --> 16:14.060
it'll have you doing things
you never imagined.

16:14.103 --> 16:16.584
Trust me.

16:16.627 --> 16:18.716
- Give us our stuff back
and point us in the direction

16:18.760 --> 16:20.153
of the nearest town.

16:20.196 --> 16:22.851
- You want to leave, fine.

16:22.894 --> 16:25.549
But I won't have you
compromising our location.

16:27.334 --> 16:30.119
Give me some time
to make arrangements.

16:32.730 --> 16:34.689
- Next time you wanna blame
the fog of war

16:34.732 --> 16:37.822
for all the shit you pulled,
just remember--

16:37.866 --> 16:41.609
when you sold me out, you'd
been out of the core for years.

16:41.652 --> 16:44.829
♪

16:44.873 --> 16:46.222
- Becca, I'm sorry.
I didn't--

16:46.266 --> 16:47.310
I didn't mean for any
of this to happen.

16:47.354 --> 16:49.182
- Someone tried to kill us.

16:49.225 --> 16:50.966
We have got to go
to the police.

16:51.010 --> 16:53.186
- We can't trust the police.
- Who the hell is she?

16:53.229 --> 16:56.798
- Her name's Nadine.
She is sort of FBI.

16:56.841 --> 16:59.322
- Sort of FBI?
What have you dragged me into?

16:59.366 --> 17:01.585
- What is this card?

17:01.629 --> 17:04.936
- It's a decryption key.

17:04.980 --> 17:06.634
To a government communications
network.

17:06.677 --> 17:08.636
But you have to access Titan's
internal system

17:08.679 --> 17:10.333
to know which one.
- Any computer in Titan?

17:10.377 --> 17:12.031
- No.

17:12.074 --> 17:14.120
All that stuff happens
on the seventh floor.

17:14.163 --> 17:17.601
- Could you get up there?
- Yeah, I could, but I won't.

17:17.645 --> 17:18.950
♪

17:18.994 --> 17:20.865
Hey, that's my stuff.

17:20.909 --> 17:22.780
- Not anymore.
You need to go into hiding.

17:22.824 --> 17:24.956
- That's insane.
- I can get you somewhere safe.

17:25.000 --> 17:26.784
- Why would I go
anywhere with you?

17:26.828 --> 17:29.874
- Rebecca, you have every right
to be mad at me.

17:29.918 --> 17:33.269
But for your own safety,
you have to trust them.

17:33.313 --> 17:35.837
♪

17:35.880 --> 17:37.926
- I'll take my chances
on my own.

17:37.969 --> 17:40.711
♪

17:40.755 --> 17:42.235
- Rebecca...

17:42.278 --> 17:44.976
- I guess she looks
similar enough.

17:45.020 --> 17:46.891
You're prettier, though.

17:46.935 --> 17:49.807
♪

17:49.851 --> 17:51.940
This is what you were
actually after, right?

17:54.290 --> 17:56.901
- Seems I don't have to explain
things to you after all.

17:58.860 --> 18:02.864
- If you impersonate her,
you'll have to go in unarmed.

18:02.907 --> 18:04.953
- Don't worry about me.

18:04.996 --> 18:06.650
I'll get what I need.

18:19.141 --> 18:21.012
- How the hell did
you get back here?

18:21.056 --> 18:23.711
- Oh, I just smiled and told
your men that you summoned me,

18:23.754 --> 18:25.191
and they ushered me
right this way.

18:25.234 --> 18:27.018
- Well, why don't you take your
fake-ass smile

18:27.062 --> 18:29.325
and get off our property?

18:31.066 --> 18:32.850
- Go fetch me a brush, Junior.

18:32.894 --> 18:34.809
This mud's a lot tougher
than I thought it would be.

18:34.852 --> 18:36.158
- [chuckles]

18:36.202 --> 18:38.291
- I believe you'll
find one in the shed.

18:45.733 --> 18:49.171
I apologize for my son's lack
of hospitality, Ms. Swagger.

18:49.215 --> 18:50.999
What can I do for you today?

18:51.042 --> 18:53.741
- I was wondering if you could
explain this to me.

19:01.227 --> 19:04.882
- Well, I must confess
my confusion.

19:04.926 --> 19:07.842
This letter would indicate
a problem with the Culp family.

19:07.885 --> 19:10.497
- Yes, but I asked around today
and it didn't take long

19:10.540 --> 19:13.021
to learn that you're the one
paying for the investigation

19:13.064 --> 19:16.024
into Rick Culp's disappearance.

19:16.067 --> 19:19.767
- Well, that's some impressive
investigating on your part,

19:19.810 --> 19:21.334
Ms. Swagger.

19:21.377 --> 19:24.902
Try to keep my charitable
efforts anonymous.

19:25.816 --> 19:29.211
- Why do you care
about Rick Culp?

19:29.255 --> 19:31.387
- His family came to me
for help.

19:32.301 --> 19:34.521
They fear he might've
been murdered.

19:34.564 --> 19:37.001
I'm just trying to be
a good neighbor.

19:37.045 --> 19:39.221
- What would happen if I just
balled this up

19:39.265 --> 19:41.180
and threw it away?
- Ooh.

19:42.268 --> 19:45.271
Well, if Bob Lee
didn't respond,

19:45.314 --> 19:51.059
I imagine that the missing
man's family would be furious.

19:51.102 --> 19:53.322
- [softly] Hmm.

19:53.366 --> 19:55.846
And if any harm came
to Bob Lee,

19:55.890 --> 19:59.328
folks would point the blame
at the Culp family.

19:59.372 --> 20:01.374
- That's a horrible thought
to even contemplate,

20:01.417 --> 20:02.940
Ms. Swagger.

20:02.984 --> 20:06.205
But I do see the logic
in your thinking.

20:07.945 --> 20:10.426
Now, as nice as it's been
meeting you,

20:10.470 --> 20:12.254
I really should get back
to my work.

20:12.298 --> 20:14.082
I know you can find
your way out.

20:14.125 --> 20:21.176
♪

20:25.354 --> 20:29.053
- I don't understand why her
husband is still alive.

20:29.097 --> 20:33.319
- You know, I had hoped
that by this time

20:33.362 --> 20:36.191
you would have
learned to use your mind

20:36.235 --> 20:40.151
before your mouth
just every once in a while.

20:40.195 --> 20:43.416
♪

20:43.459 --> 20:45.809
When these are clean,
I'll see you inside.

20:45.853 --> 20:49.552
♪

20:49.596 --> 20:51.380
- Ma, I can't because
it's a secret.

20:51.424 --> 20:52.990
If I tell you,
it won't be a secret.

20:54.905 --> 20:56.385
Yeah, I'll try to call you
in a few days.

20:57.430 --> 21:00.563
No, Ma, no, I'm not gonna
tell you from where.

21:00.607 --> 21:03.436
[suspenseful music]

21:07.048 --> 21:07.440
.

21:07.483 --> 21:09.442
- Your ride's here.
- Hey.

21:10.443 --> 21:12.096
This photo's
dated July, 1970.

21:12.140 --> 21:13.924
That's the same month that you
said you saw my dad

21:13.968 --> 21:15.578
kill civilians.

21:15.622 --> 21:17.798
- My accident occurred
the night we got back

21:17.841 --> 21:18.842
from that mission.

21:20.191 --> 21:22.019
- Couldn't have been too
disturbed by what you saw

21:22.063 --> 21:25.806
if you partied all night
and smiled for the photo.

21:25.849 --> 21:28.025
- I smiled because your father
was sending me home.

21:28.069 --> 21:31.725
[rhythm & blues playing]

21:31.768 --> 21:35.990
♪

21:36.033 --> 21:38.471
- Really?
Thanks for waiting on me, guys.

21:38.514 --> 21:40.647
- Took you long enough.
- Oh, come on, now.

21:40.690 --> 21:42.649
Oh, shut it.
Here.

21:42.692 --> 21:44.607
Where's my whiskey?

21:44.651 --> 21:47.480
♪

21:47.523 --> 21:48.916
- One of you guys gonna
deal me in?

21:48.959 --> 21:50.831
- Sure, sarge.
Pull up a chair.

21:50.874 --> 21:53.616
♪

21:53.660 --> 21:56.532
[indistinct chatter]

21:58.534 --> 22:00.101
- You're looking a little glum

22:00.144 --> 22:02.843
for someone who just survived
a suicide mission.

22:02.886 --> 22:09.458
♪

22:09.502 --> 22:10.894
- [grunts]

22:10.938 --> 22:14.420
You forget what you
signed up for, Ramon?

22:14.463 --> 22:17.423
Hmm?

22:17.466 --> 22:19.512
This unit is responsible
for taking out

22:19.555 --> 22:21.644
anyone who threatens
the war effort.

22:21.688 --> 22:24.212
Collateral damage
is unavoidable.

22:24.255 --> 22:26.867
- Collateral damage?

22:26.910 --> 22:30.000
- Hey.
Look at me.

22:30.044 --> 22:31.567
Look at me, God damn it.

22:31.611 --> 22:33.569
[dramatic music]

22:33.613 --> 22:38.400
You don't like it, there's only
two ways out of this.

22:39.793 --> 22:42.535
One of them's in a body bag.

22:42.578 --> 22:44.885
The other is you keep
your ass in line.

22:44.928 --> 22:47.888
[dark music]

22:47.931 --> 22:50.499
♪

22:50.543 --> 22:52.109
Choose wisely.

22:52.153 --> 22:57.724
♪

22:57.767 --> 23:00.422
- I knew Earl was right.

23:00.466 --> 23:02.555
I got myself into
the situation.

23:03.773 --> 23:06.123
And only I could
get myself out.

23:17.874 --> 23:19.746
Your father acted surprised...
Aah!

23:19.789 --> 23:21.922
and let the guys believe
it was an accident.

23:21.965 --> 23:23.706
Then he signed paperwork

23:23.750 --> 23:26.622
saying I was injured
during the mission.

23:26.666 --> 23:30.670
In exchange,
I smiled for the picture

23:30.713 --> 23:33.542
the next day and kept
my mouth shut.

23:35.588 --> 23:37.938
Years later,
I learned that our mission

23:37.981 --> 23:40.941
in Cambodia wasn't even
about the war.

23:40.984 --> 23:45.119
The general was a drug smuggler
who wouldn't share his routes.

23:45.162 --> 23:47.817
That woman we killed
was a prostitute.

23:47.861 --> 23:49.602
- That's bullshit.
- Bob Lee--

23:49.645 --> 23:51.038
- No, there's no way my dad
would have encouraged

23:51.081 --> 23:54.041
that kind of cowardice.
- Cowardice?

23:54.084 --> 23:56.522
Shooting myself was the single
bravest thing I did

23:56.565 --> 23:58.306
during the war.

23:58.349 --> 24:03.093
Your father even said as much
when he called me years later.

24:03.137 --> 24:04.573
- He called you?

24:04.617 --> 24:06.662
- Just a few weeks
before he died.

24:06.706 --> 24:09.317
He said he wanted
to expose Atlas.

24:09.360 --> 24:11.667
- Well, did he say why he was
finally ready to come clean?

24:11.711 --> 24:14.757
- No, he was killed
before we could meet.

24:14.801 --> 24:17.717
- What do you know
about Atlas now?

24:17.760 --> 24:19.936
- Nothing.

24:21.285 --> 24:23.984
But there is someone else
you could talk to.

24:24.027 --> 24:25.899
♪

24:25.942 --> 24:28.205
Katherine Mayfield.

24:28.249 --> 24:30.338
After Vietnam,
she became something

24:30.381 --> 24:35.561
of a dark lord in the Pentagon
until she retired abruptly

24:35.604 --> 24:37.911
a few years back.
- Where is she?

24:37.954 --> 24:40.522
- Last I heard,

24:40.566 --> 24:42.959
she was committed to a
psychiatric hospital upstate.

24:43.003 --> 24:44.613
- So she's crazy?

24:44.657 --> 24:45.614
- [chuckles]

24:45.658 --> 24:47.050
Not necessarily.

24:47.094 --> 24:48.704
- Well, either way,
we should talk to her.

24:48.748 --> 24:52.186
- It would be much wiser
to disappear.

24:52.229 --> 24:54.580
- There's no sense in running.
We got something Atlas wants.

24:54.623 --> 24:55.885
They're not gonna stop
coming after it.

24:55.929 --> 24:59.280
- My advice--
give it back to them.

24:59.323 --> 25:03.023
Or get as far away from it
as possible.

25:03.066 --> 25:06.374
The more you dig,
the more you'll suffer.

25:06.417 --> 25:13.599
♪

25:14.600 --> 25:15.992
[beeping]

25:16.036 --> 25:22.999
♪

25:23.043 --> 25:25.219
- The vehicle is clean.

25:25.262 --> 25:28.222
Shouldn't have any problem
getting where you're going.

25:28.265 --> 25:29.876
- I always thought
drug traffickers

25:29.919 --> 25:31.921
prefer flashier rides.
- [laughs]

25:31.965 --> 25:34.620
Only if they wanna get caught.

25:36.317 --> 25:38.841
Something on your mind, son?

25:40.103 --> 25:41.931
- You left Phoenix,
but my dad stayed.

25:41.975 --> 25:44.238
Presumably kept doing
horrible things.

25:44.281 --> 25:46.762
I'm just wondering why.

25:47.807 --> 25:49.722
- Your father loved
his country.

25:49.765 --> 25:52.899
And like a lot of people,
he'd lost his way.

25:52.942 --> 25:55.075
Take some comfort in the fact

25:55.118 --> 25:57.251
that he wanted
to make it right.

25:57.294 --> 26:01.342
He just...never got the chance.

26:01.385 --> 26:04.171
[unsettling music]

26:04.214 --> 26:10.656
♪

26:21.231 --> 26:23.146
- Hey.
- Hey.

26:23.190 --> 26:25.105
- Hi, I, uh--I'm
headed into town.

26:25.148 --> 26:26.759
Do you need anything?
- Oh, no, I'm good.

26:26.802 --> 26:28.064
Thank you.

26:29.370 --> 26:32.765
- Wow, Bob Lee's really making
some progress.

26:32.808 --> 26:35.115
- Yeah, well, he thinks
he can do anything.

26:35.158 --> 26:37.291
- That's not new, Julie.

26:37.334 --> 26:39.989
You know, I distinctly remember
you saying that you liked

26:40.033 --> 26:41.991
that about him when
you guys first met.

26:42.992 --> 26:44.820
- Yeah, that's true.

26:45.995 --> 26:48.824
I guess I thought after all
this time, though,

26:48.868 --> 26:51.000
you know, we would take on
the world together

26:51.044 --> 26:54.047
instead of him doing it
all by himself.

26:54.090 --> 26:56.789
My mistake was wishing
and hoping

26:56.832 --> 26:59.313
instead of making it happen.

27:00.053 --> 27:02.142
But I did figure out
that Red Bama

27:02.185 --> 27:03.883
had that letter sent today.

27:03.926 --> 27:07.277
Yeah, I had him explain
it to me, and he, uh,

27:07.321 --> 27:09.105
well, he showed
his hand a little.

27:09.149 --> 27:11.891
- The cattle rancher?
How is he mixed up in all this?

27:11.934 --> 27:14.154
- Yeah, he's the only one who
knows the truth about who

27:14.197 --> 27:15.764
killed Bob Lee's father.

27:15.808 --> 27:18.114
[dramatic music]

27:18.158 --> 27:20.029
- Hi, Rebecca.
- Hey.

27:20.073 --> 27:27.123
♪

27:29.735 --> 27:30.736
[beeping]

27:30.779 --> 27:37.830
♪

27:52.453 --> 27:57.806
[beeping]

27:57.850 --> 27:59.112
♪

27:59.155 --> 28:00.156
[beeping]

28:00.200 --> 28:07.250
♪

28:17.260 --> 28:18.218
[camera shutter clicks]

28:18.261 --> 28:25.312
♪

28:30.317 --> 28:31.318
[camera shutter clicks]

28:31.361 --> 28:36.410
♪

28:36.453 --> 28:37.846
[cell phone vibrates]

28:37.890 --> 28:38.847
- Don't answer.
Could be Atlas.

28:38.891 --> 28:40.153
- Hello?

28:40.196 --> 28:41.545
- Hey, I'm trying to get
a hold of Nadine.

28:41.589 --> 28:43.765
Why won't she answer?
- It's Bob Lee.

28:43.809 --> 28:47.551
- Uh, yeah, she won't pick up
because she's in Titan,

28:47.595 --> 28:50.163
which blocks all electronic
communication inside or out.

28:50.206 --> 28:51.860
- You sent her in blind
and alone?

28:51.904 --> 28:53.862
- No one sent her.
Nadine's calling the shots.

28:53.906 --> 28:55.429
- All right, just text
us your location

28:55.472 --> 28:56.822
and we'll be there soon.

28:56.865 --> 29:03.916
♪

29:05.004 --> 29:06.005
[camera shutter clicks]

29:06.048 --> 29:09.965
♪

29:10.009 --> 29:10.966
[beeping]

29:11.010 --> 29:17.277
♪

29:17.320 --> 29:18.408
[buzzing]

29:18.452 --> 29:20.106
♪

29:20.149 --> 29:21.455
[buzzing]

29:26.634 --> 29:26.808
.

29:26.852 --> 29:29.289
- Back when Earl was killed,

29:29.332 --> 29:31.247
Red Bama owned two
slaughterhouses

29:32.074 --> 29:32.988
with cattle on 100 acres.

29:33.032 --> 29:36.296
He was just a--a
pissant upstart.

29:36.339 --> 29:39.908
So how is it Red pulled the
strings behind Earl's murder?

29:39.952 --> 29:42.302
- I don't think that Red
was at the center of it.

29:42.345 --> 29:44.608
- Well, if that's the case,
how do you connect Red

29:44.652 --> 29:46.697
to the murder?
- Well, through Jimmy Poole.

29:46.741 --> 29:49.526
Look, I don't think that Jimmy
escaped prison work detail

29:49.570 --> 29:50.832
at Bama's slaughterhouse.

29:50.876 --> 29:53.530
I think that Red helped
get him out.

29:53.574 --> 29:54.749
- Supposition.

29:55.663 --> 29:56.925
- Okay.

29:56.969 --> 30:00.015
You want the facts.
- I do.

30:00.059 --> 30:03.540
- Three months after Earl dies,
Red gets a sweetheart deal

30:03.584 --> 30:05.847
for 2,000 acres
of government land.

30:05.891 --> 30:07.544
Within a year,
he gets appointed

30:07.588 --> 30:09.372
under-secretary in the
Agricultural Department,

30:09.416 --> 30:11.897
despite being unqualified
for the job.

30:12.811 --> 30:14.334
- It's thin.

30:14.769 --> 30:16.597
But it's something.

30:16.640 --> 30:18.338
How far are you willing
to go with it?

30:18.381 --> 30:20.383
- All the way.

30:20.427 --> 30:21.907
[suspenseful music]

30:21.950 --> 30:22.995
- Morning.

30:24.344 --> 30:25.954
[beeping]

30:25.998 --> 30:28.827
- Don't think
I've seen you around.

30:28.870 --> 30:30.002
- It's my first day.

30:30.045 --> 30:31.438
[beeping]

30:31.481 --> 30:35.050
♪

30:35.094 --> 30:39.576
[police sirens blaring]

30:39.620 --> 30:40.795
♪

30:40.839 --> 30:41.970
- Shit.

30:42.014 --> 30:49.282
♪

30:49.978 --> 30:52.894
- Hey, what's the situation?
- Nadine is blown.

30:52.938 --> 30:54.635
She needs some
help getting out.

30:54.678 --> 30:55.984
- Plus some cops just walked in
that did not look like

30:56.028 --> 30:57.856
typical DCPD.

30:57.899 --> 30:59.901
- You got a clean phone?

31:00.946 --> 31:03.426
[beeping]
[line ringing]

31:03.470 --> 31:05.385
- 911, what's your emergency?
- There's a bomb inside

31:05.428 --> 31:06.777
the headquarters
at Titan Incorporated.

31:06.821 --> 31:08.954
It's about to go off.

31:08.997 --> 31:12.958
♪

31:13.001 --> 31:15.961
[alarms blaring]

31:16.004 --> 31:17.614
♪

31:17.658 --> 31:19.312
[door buzzes and clicks]

31:21.009 --> 31:23.316
- Ladies and gentlemen,
please proceed

31:23.359 --> 31:25.535
to the nearest exit.

31:25.579 --> 31:27.711
[alarm blaring]

31:27.755 --> 31:31.541
Ladies and gentlemen, please
proceed to the nearest exit.

31:31.585 --> 31:32.934
- Hey, hey, I'm with Homeland.

31:32.978 --> 31:34.588
You gotta leave
the building immediately.

31:34.631 --> 31:35.806
- Sir, you can't come in here.
- There's a bomb.

31:35.850 --> 31:37.069
Did you hear me?
There is a bomb

31:37.112 --> 31:38.766
in this building.
- I don't care--

31:38.809 --> 31:39.941
- It's been confirmed.
We all gotta evacuate.

31:39.985 --> 31:41.464
- You hear that?

31:41.508 --> 31:42.944
People, there's a bomb
in this building!

31:42.988 --> 31:45.425
It could go off any minute!
Let's move, move!

31:45.468 --> 31:46.643
- This way, this way, everyone.
Come on.

31:46.687 --> 31:49.777
[commotion]

31:49.820 --> 31:52.954
[suspenseful music]

31:52.998 --> 31:56.784
♪

31:56.827 --> 31:58.655
- Unit three, we're headed up
the north stairwell.

31:58.699 --> 32:01.702
- Copy that.
- Step aside.

32:01.745 --> 32:03.095
Come on, people.
Move it.

32:03.138 --> 32:06.011
♪

32:06.054 --> 32:07.490
Hey, you, hold it!

32:07.534 --> 32:12.931
♪

32:12.974 --> 32:13.932
[beeping]

32:13.975 --> 32:19.938
♪

32:19.981 --> 32:21.678
[beeping]

32:21.722 --> 32:28.685
♪

32:28.729 --> 32:30.513
- Sir, you have
to evacuate immediately.

32:30.557 --> 32:32.167
- I left my keys in the desk.
I gotta go grab them.

32:32.211 --> 32:33.647
- No, I can't let
you do that, sir.

32:33.690 --> 32:34.909
- You're carrying a Maxim 9.

32:34.953 --> 32:35.910
Is that standard issue
for a c--

32:35.954 --> 32:38.652
[both grunting]

32:38.695 --> 32:40.523
♪

32:40.567 --> 32:42.656
- [grunts]

32:42.699 --> 32:44.788
- Clear the 7th floor.
She hasn't left the building.

32:44.832 --> 32:47.791
[sirens blaring]

32:47.835 --> 32:52.013
♪

32:52.057 --> 32:53.754
- At least the authorities
are taking our bomb threat

32:53.797 --> 32:55.060
pretty seriously.

32:55.103 --> 32:56.583
- It would be disturbing
if they didn't.

32:56.626 --> 33:02.197
♪

33:02.241 --> 33:04.721
- Shouldn't have let Bob Lee
talk me into staying out here.

33:04.765 --> 33:06.810
- You're not the first person
he's done that to.

33:06.854 --> 33:09.944
Hogging the hero spotlight
is one of his many talents.

33:11.467 --> 33:12.860
- So now what?

33:12.903 --> 33:14.775
How's Atlas likely
to respond to this?

33:14.818 --> 33:16.603
- They'll send in half
a dozen hitters,

33:16.646 --> 33:18.474
activate any sleeper agents
who've been

33:18.518 --> 33:19.954
working at Titan all along,
and send an extraction team

33:19.998 --> 33:21.608
for when it's done.

33:21.651 --> 33:22.913
- So somewhere around here,
they have people waiting

33:22.957 --> 33:24.741
to pick them up?
- Yeah.

33:24.785 --> 33:27.744
- Let's find them.
- Get out.

33:27.788 --> 33:29.790
If Nadine escaped,
she'll need a ride, ASAP.

33:29.833 --> 33:30.834
- Right, yeah.

33:30.878 --> 33:33.054
[car engine starts]

33:33.098 --> 33:36.057
[alarms blaring]

33:36.101 --> 33:43.151
♪

34:07.784 --> 34:10.831
[tense music]

34:10.874 --> 34:17.925
♪

34:24.975 --> 34:26.673
[gunfire]

34:26.716 --> 34:28.805
- I'm in pursuit of target
on the sixth floor.

34:28.849 --> 34:31.547
- All agents converge
on the sixth floor.

34:31.591 --> 34:34.637
Code green. You're authorized
to terminate target on sight.

34:40.382 --> 34:40.556
.

34:40.600 --> 34:43.081
[unsettling music]

34:43.646 --> 34:45.126
♪

34:45.170 --> 34:47.955
- That's the fifth time that
police van's circled by.

34:49.087 --> 34:50.523
- You're right.

34:50.566 --> 34:53.308
Or else we're about to start
a war with legit cops.

34:53.352 --> 34:55.702
- Why would legit cops be
circling around outside

34:55.745 --> 34:57.225
the security perimeter?

34:58.400 --> 35:00.098
- I'll get in position.

35:02.317 --> 35:05.407
[alarms continue blaring]

35:08.584 --> 35:10.108
- Hey!

35:27.299 --> 35:31.172
- [screaming]
- [grunting]

35:31.216 --> 35:33.435
♪

35:33.479 --> 35:36.438
[both grunting]

35:36.482 --> 35:43.532
♪

35:44.446 --> 35:46.579
[tires squealing]

35:46.622 --> 35:53.629
♪

36:29.099 --> 36:31.319
- DCPD on sight.
All agents pull back.

36:36.585 --> 36:38.283
- I surrender.
I'm unarmed.

36:38.326 --> 36:40.110
- All right, just keep
those hands in the air.

36:42.287 --> 36:45.246
Slowly.
- I'm unarmed, I surrender.

36:45.290 --> 36:46.682
- Okay. That's far enough.

36:46.726 --> 36:49.685
[tense, suspenseful music]

36:49.729 --> 36:56.301
♪

36:56.344 --> 36:59.173
- While you were gone,
two dozen more cops showed up.

36:59.217 --> 37:01.044
How does this end well
for Nadine?

37:02.698 --> 37:04.483
- It doesn't.

37:04.526 --> 37:06.528
[indistinct radio chatter]

37:06.572 --> 37:13.622
♪

37:19.672 --> 37:21.239
- Ms. Swagger.

37:22.544 --> 37:24.416
After thinking about it
for a bit,

37:24.459 --> 37:27.332
my son would like to apologize
to you for the way

37:27.375 --> 37:29.421
he spoke to you before.

37:30.683 --> 37:32.250
Junior?

37:34.252 --> 37:37.298
- I'm sorry for cussing you
and insulting you,

37:37.342 --> 37:39.344
Mrs. Swagger.

37:39.387 --> 37:41.824
I actually think you have
a beautiful smile.

37:43.739 --> 37:45.219
- Thank you.

37:51.269 --> 37:53.575
- I hope you'll accept
my apology as well.

37:53.619 --> 37:56.186
I should have
raised him better.

37:56.230 --> 37:58.232
- Well, apology accepted.

37:58.276 --> 37:59.712
♪

37:59.755 --> 38:01.583
Especially since I thought you
were here to talk me out

38:01.627 --> 38:03.455
of a wrongful death suit
that Sam was filing

38:03.498 --> 38:05.413
against you today.

38:06.327 --> 38:09.330
- I'm not real big on wasting
time, Ms. Swagger.

38:09.374 --> 38:12.638
And given your husband's
stubborn nature,

38:12.681 --> 38:15.641
I don't imagine I can talk
a Swagger out of anything.

38:15.684 --> 38:17.730
♪

38:17.773 --> 38:20.863
I was just here
to speak with Sam--

38:20.907 --> 38:23.649
to reason with him man to man.
- Well, Sam is out.

38:23.692 --> 38:25.520
- I can see that.

38:25.564 --> 38:29.263
And it looks to me like
the rumors about Sam closing

38:29.307 --> 38:33.180
up shop might be true.
- Yeah, he is retiring.

38:33.223 --> 38:37.271
- Good for him, good for him.
He deserves a rest.

38:37.315 --> 38:39.839
It seems kind of odd to me
that he'd take on a new case

38:39.882 --> 38:41.710
this close to the end.

38:41.754 --> 38:44.800
- Well, Sam's always had
a knack for picking good cases.

38:44.844 --> 38:47.368
Maybe he wants to go out
with a win.

38:47.412 --> 38:48.935
- [chuckles]

38:48.978 --> 38:51.590
Well, I think you're gonna
have a hard time coming up

38:51.633 --> 38:55.289
with any evidence to back your
claim after more than 30 years.

38:55.333 --> 38:57.378
♪

38:57.422 --> 38:59.554
- Yet here you are.

38:59.598 --> 39:02.165
Makes me wonder why.

39:02.209 --> 39:05.343
Maybe a jury will wonder,
too.

39:05.386 --> 39:06.387
- [chuckles]

39:09.695 --> 39:13.873
Know that if you go forward
with this,

39:13.916 --> 39:16.832
I intend not only to win,

39:16.876 --> 39:20.445
I intend to make everyone
involved very sorry

39:20.488 --> 39:22.316
that they bothered.

39:24.536 --> 39:27.277
You tell Sam I dropped by
to wish him well.

39:27.321 --> 39:32.195
Not many people in this life
make it to retirement.

39:32.239 --> 39:35.285
He should consider himself
one of the lucky ones.

39:35.329 --> 39:37.462
[door closes]

39:37.505 --> 39:38.767
- All right, let's think.

39:38.811 --> 39:40.421
- All right, if the real
cops have her,

39:40.465 --> 39:42.205
she's probably here
at central booking.

39:42.249 --> 39:44.643
If not, she's already dead.

39:44.686 --> 39:46.906
- Let's assume she's alive
and figure out a way

39:46.949 --> 39:48.777
to get in there.

39:48.821 --> 39:50.736
- So what, we're--we're gonna
assault a police station?

39:50.779 --> 39:53.478
- Not we, Harris.
- This is insane.

39:53.521 --> 39:55.436
- All we need to do is get
Nadine back.

39:55.480 --> 39:56.959
Then she can tell us
what's on the card.

39:57.003 --> 39:59.266
- I'm afraid this whole
discussion is pointless, guys.

39:59.309 --> 40:00.876
I mean, that police station
is more secure

40:00.920 --> 40:02.922
than the Pentagon.
- She's right.

40:02.965 --> 40:05.490
After 9-11, all
the D.C. government buildings

40:05.533 --> 40:07.405
got a major security upgrade.

40:07.448 --> 40:08.971
You'd need a tank
to get in there.

40:09.015 --> 40:10.451
- If we can't get in,
Atlas can't get in, either.

40:10.495 --> 40:12.758
- There's no official ID
Atlas can't spoof.

40:12.801 --> 40:15.456
I'm sure
they're already inside.

40:15.500 --> 40:17.240
- Then we sit on the place
and see if they move her.

40:17.284 --> 40:19.329
- What if they already have?

40:22.420 --> 40:24.247
[buzzer]
[click]

40:25.466 --> 40:27.033
- Get up.
You're being moved.

40:27.076 --> 40:29.514
- Moved to where?
- Hands through the bars now.

40:29.557 --> 40:30.732
- I want a lawyer.

40:30.776 --> 40:34.040
- Non-compliant inmate.
Now!

40:34.083 --> 40:37.043
[intense music]

40:37.086 --> 40:40.525
♪

40:40.568 --> 40:43.528
- Hey, look, I'm FBI,
and you don't understand

40:43.571 --> 40:44.616
what's going on here.

40:44.659 --> 40:45.791
- [grunts]
- [groans]

40:45.834 --> 40:52.885
♪

41:04.592 --> 41:05.811
[dramatic musical sting]
